 Here is a C++ program that uses recursion to find the nth Fibonacci number:

```cpp
#include <iostream>

// Function to calculate nth Fibonacci number using recursion
int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) {
        return n;
    }
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    int nthFibonacci = fibonacci(n);
    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << nthFibonacci << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To use this program, simply enter the value of `n` when prompted, and the program will calculate and display the nth Fibonacci number.

Note that this recursive approach is not the most efficient way to calculate Fibonacci numbers, especially for large values of `n`, due to the repeated calculations of the same values. For larger values of `n`, an iterative approach or memoization technique is recommended to improve performance.

 Here is a simple HTML website with JavaScript code that displays a random joke when a button is clicked.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Random Joke Generator</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f7f7f7;
        }

        .container {
            text-align: center;
        }

        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Random Joke Generator</h1>
        <button onclick="tellJoke()">Tell me a joke!</button>
        <p id="joke"></p>
    </div>

    <script>
        const jokes = [
            "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything!",
            "I told my wife she was drawing her eyebrows too high. She looked surprised.",
            "Why don't some couples go to the gym? Because some relationships don't work out.",
            "I'm reading a book on anti-gravity. It's impossible to put down."
        ];

        function tellJoke() {
            const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
            document.getElementById("joke").innerText = jokes[randomIndex];
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

This code creates a simple webpage with a button that, when clicked, will display a random joke from the array of jokes defined in the JavaScript code. The jokes are displayed in a paragraph element with the ID "joke". The JavaScript code uses the `Math.random()` function to generate a random index within the range of the array's indices, and then uses that index to select a joke from the array. The selected joke is then displayed in the paragraph element.

 To find the number of full binary trees with n vertices, we can use the concept of Catalan numbers. The nth Catalan number C_n is the number of full binary trees with n vertices. The nth Catalan number can be calculated using the following formula:

C_n = (1/(n+1)) * (2n choose n) = (2(2n)! / ((n+1)! * n!))

Here is a Python function that implements the calculation of the nth Catalan number using the above formula:

```python
def factorial(n):
    """Calculate the factorial of a number."""
    if n == 0:
        return 1
    else:
        return n * factorial(n-1)

def catalan_number(n):
    """Calculate the nth Catalan number."""
    return factorial(2*n) // (factorial(n+1) * factorial(n))

def B_n(n):
    """Calculate the number of full binary trees with n vertices (B_n)."""
    return catalan_number(n)

# Example usage:
n = 5
print(f"The number of full binary trees with {n} vertices is: {B_n(n)}")
```

This function first defines a helper function `factorial` to calculate the factorial of a number. Then, it defines the `catalan_number` function to calculate the nth Catalan number using the formula mentioned above. Finally, the `B_n` function calls the `catalan_number` function to find the number of full binary trees with n vertices.

Note that the `//` operator in Python is used for integer division, which ensures that the result is an integer value.

